The paper deals with the analysis of algorithms for linear programming and polytopes, which are topics typically studied in computer science subfields such as data structures (cs.DS), computational geometry (cs.CG), numerical analysis (cs.NA), computational complexity (cs.CC), and game theory (cs.GT). The focus on the simplex method and its smoothed complexity suggests that cs.NA and cs.CC are particularly relevant, but the use of randomized algorithms and the study of polytopes also point towards cs.DS and cs.CG. The mention of the Hirsch conjecture and the analysis of walks on polytopes further support the relevance of cs.CG.
